I think some work needs to be done to port Cantera to 64 bit machines.   
Type &quot;doublereal&quot; is defined in config.h, and can be mapped in  
principle to &quot;double&quot; or &quot;float&quot;.  But unfortunately there are places  
in Cantera where &quot;double&quot; is used explicitly (especially in connection  
with CVODE), so currently &quot;doublereal&quot;  must be defined to be &quot;double&quot;.  
  There may be issues with &quot;long int&quot; vs. &quot;int&quot; also.

I don&#39;t know if this is the problem. You might try building a Cantera  
C++ application, instead of building the Cantera Python package, which  
might be easier to debug.  For example, go into &quot;examples/cxx&quot; and type  
&quot;make&quot;, or create a new demo application by typing &quot;ctnew&quot; and try to  
compile it.  Good luck!


